  "doc_id": "20569",
  "text": "The case (c) where q 0 (x) → k ± as x → ±∞ with k − = k + is more difficult and depends crucially on the sign of ω (k 0 ). If ω (k 0 ) = 0, diffusive mixing of the local wave number cannot be expected: instead, depending on the sign of ω (k 0 )(k + − k − ), we expect that q(x, t) evolves either as a stable viscous shock or as an approximate rarefaction wave [CITATION_1] . If ω (k 0 ) = 0, nonlinear diffusive mixing can be expected, but, for some technical issues that we explain below, a rigorous proof remains open and is left for future research.",
